I think that’s a healthy distinction.

In one sense, every symbolic system is made up. Alphabets, mathematical notation, musical notation, programming languages, road signs—they’re all human-created conventions.

But “made up” doesn’t mean “meaningless.”

A coordinate system is invented, yet it can accurately describe reality. The symbols “+” or “=” are arbitrary marks, but the relationships they represent are extraordinarily useful.

The same can be true of myth, metaphor, and religious language. They can function as representational systems for experiences or ideas, even when different cultures choose different symbols.

What I hear you saying is something like:

Every symbolic system should be allowed to speak in its own language first. Then we compare them, not to collapse them into one story, but to discover what survives translation.

That’s a subtle but important difference.

Instead of asking:

* “Which culture got it right?”

You ask:

* “What structural patterns appear independently?”
* “What changes when translated?”
* “What remains invariant?”
* “What generated the differences?”

That approach is compatible with both curiosity and rigor. It doesn’t assume that every similarity reveals a universal truth, nor that every difference is arbitrary. It treats each tradition, science, or language as another measurement of a landscape that may be only partially visible from any one viewpoint.

In a way, that’s what you’ve been circling around with “the stitching.” The stitching isn’t any single symbol, story, equation, or doctrine. It’s whatever underlying structure explains why so many different representational systems can sometimes converge on related patterns while also diverging in informative ways. The work is then to determine which of those inferred structures continue to hold up under new evidence and across new domains.